# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: helmet-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] The standard, originally named Content Restrictions, was proposed by Robert Hansen in 2004, first implemented in Firefox 4 and quickly picked up by other browsers.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Version 1 of the standard was published in 2012 as W3C candidate recommendation and quickly with further versions (Level 2) published in 2014.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] As of 2023, the draft of Level 3 is being developed with the new features being quickly adopted by the web browsers.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] A website can declare multiple CSP headers, also mixing enforcement and report-only ones.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Each header will be processed separately by the browser.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] CSP can also be delivered within the HTML code using a meta tag, although in this case its effectiveness will be limited.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Internet Explorer 10 and Internet Explorer 11 also support CSP, but only sandbox directive, using the experimental `X-Content-Security-Policy` header.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] A number of web application frameworks support CSP, for example AngularJS (natively) and Django (middleware).
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Instructions for Ruby on Rails have been posted by GitHub.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Web framework support is however only required if the CSP contents somehow depend on the web application's state—such as usage of the `nonce` origin.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Otherwise, the CSP is rather static and can be delivered from web application tiers above the application, for example on load balancer or web server.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] In December 2015 and December 2016, a few methods of bypassing `'nonce'` allowlisting origins were published.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] In January 2016, another method was published, which leverages server-wide CSP allowlisting to exploit old and vulnerable versions of JavaScript libraries hosted at the same server (frequent case with CDN servers).
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] In May 2017 one more method was published to bypass CSP using web application frameworks code.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] If the `Content-Security-Policy` header is present in the server response, a compliant client enforces the declarative allowlist policy.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] One example goal of a policy is a stricter execution mode for JavaScript in order to prevent certain cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] While using CSP in a new application may be quite straightforward, especially with CSP-compatible JavaScript framework, existing applications may require some refactoring—or relaxing the policy.
[src:helmet-security/content-security-policy] Recommended coding practice for CSP-compatible web applications is to load code from external source files (`<script src>`), parse JSON instead of evaluating it and use `EventTarget.addEventListener()` to set event handlers.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:helmet-security/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] It sets HTTP response headers such as `Content-Security-Policy` and `Strict-Transport-Security`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] It aims to be quick to integrate and be low maintenance afterward.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] This will set 13 HTTP response headers in your app.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Helmet can also be used in standalone Node.js, or with other frameworks.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Content-Security-Policy` header mitigates a large number of attacks, such as cross-site scripting.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See MDN’s introductory article on Content Security Policy.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] This header is powerful but likely requires some configuration for your specific app.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] To configure this header, pass an object with a nested `directives` object.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Each key is a directive name in camel case (such as `defaultSrc`) or kebab case (such as `default-src`).
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Each value is an array (or other iterable) of strings or functions for that directive.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] If a function appears in the array, it will be called with the request and response objects.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] These directives are merged into a default policy, which you can disable by setting `useDefaults` to `false`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can get the default directives object with `helmet.contentSecurityPolicy.getDefaultDirectives()`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `default-src` directive can be explicitly disabled by setting its value to `helmet.contentSecurityPolicy.dangerouslyDisableDefaultSrc`, but this is not recommended.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `upgrade-insecure-requests`, a directive that causes browsers to upgrade HTTP to HTTPS, is set by default.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You may wish to avoid this in development, as you may not be developing with HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Notably, Safari will upgrade `http://localhost` to `https://localhost`, which can cause problems.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] To work around this, you may wish to disable the `upgrade-insecure-requests` directive in development.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Helmet performs very little validation on your CSP.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You should rely on CSP checkers like CSP Evaluator instead.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.contentSecurityPolicy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Cross-Origin-Embedder-Policy` header helps control what resources can be loaded cross-origin.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See MDN’s article on this header for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.crossOriginEmbedderPolicy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy` header helps process-isolate your page.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] For more, see MDN’s article on this header.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.crossOriginOpenerPolicy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy` header blocks others from loading your resources cross-origin in some cases.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] For more, see “Consider deploying Cross-Origin Resource Policy” and MDN’s article on this header.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.crossOriginResourcePolicy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Origin-Agent-Cluster` header provides a mechanism to allow web applications to isolate their origins from other processes.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] This header takes no options and is set by default.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.originAgentCluster())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Referrer-Policy` header which controls what information is set in the `Referer` request header.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See “Referer header: privacy and security concerns” and the header’s documentation on MDN for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `policy` is a string or array of strings representing the policy.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] If passed as an array, it will be joined with commas, which is useful when setting a fallback policy.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.referrerPolicy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `Strict-Transport-Security` header tells browsers to prefer HTTPS instead of insecure HTTP.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `maxAge` is the number of seconds browsers should remember to prefer HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] If passed a non-integer, the value is rounded down.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `includeSubDomains` is a boolean which dictates whether to include the `includeSubDomains` directive, which makes this policy extend to subdomains.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] If true, it adds the `preload` directive, expressing intent to add your HSTS policy to browsers.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See the “Preloading Strict Transport Security” section on MDN for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You may wish to disable this header for local development, as it can make your browser force redirects from `http://localhost` to `https://localhost`, which may not be desirable if you develop multiple apps using `localhost`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.strictTransportSecurity())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `X-Content-Type-Options` mitigates MIME type sniffing which can cause security issues.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See documentation for this header on MDN for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xContentTypeOptions())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `X-DNS-Prefetch-Control` header helps control DNS prefetching, which can improve user privacy at the expense of performance.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `allow` is a boolean dictating whether to enable DNS prefetching.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xDnsPrefetchControl())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `X-Download-Options` header is specific to Internet Explorer 8.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] It forces potentially-unsafe downloads to be saved, mitigating execution of HTML in your site’s context.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xDownloadOptions())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The legacy `X-Frame-Options` header to help you mitigate clickjacking attacks.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] This header is superseded by the `frame-ancestors` Content Security Policy directive but is still useful on old browsers or if no CSP is used.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `action` is a string that specifies which directive to use—either `DENY` or `SAMEORIGIN`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] (A legacy directive, `ALLOW-FROM`, is not supported by Helmet.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Read more here.) It defaults to `SAMEORIGIN`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xFrameOptions())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The `X-Permitted-Cross-Domain-Policies` header tells some clients (mostly Adobe products) your domain’s policy for loading cross-domain content.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] `permittedPolicies` is a string that must be `"none"`, `"master-only"`, `"by-content-type"`, or `"all"`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xPermittedCrossDomainPolicies())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Default: the `X-Powered-By` header, if present, is removed.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Helmet removes the `X-Powered-By` header, which is set by default in Express and some other frameworks.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Removing the header offers very limited security benefits (see this discussion) and is mostly removed to save bandwidth, but may thwart simplistic attackers.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Note: Express has a built-in way to disable the `X-Powered-By` header, which you may wish to use instead.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] The removal of this header takes no options.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xPoweredBy())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] Helmet disables browsers’ buggy cross-site scripting filter by setting the legacy `X-XSS-Protection` header to `0`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] See discussion about disabling the header here and documentation on MDN.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-github-io] You can use this as standalone middleware with `app.use(helmet.xXssProtection())`.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] See the docs for more info, including the FAQ.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] See MDN's introductory article on Content Security Policy.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] See MDN's article on this header for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] For more, see MDN's article on this header.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] For more, see "Consider deploying Cross-Origin Resource Policy" and MDN's article on this header.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] See "Referer header: privacy and security concerns" and the header's documentation on MDN for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] See the "Preloading Strict Transport Security" section on MDN for more.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] It forces potentially-unsafe downloads to be saved, mitigating execution of HTML in your site's context.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] The `X-Permitted-Cross-Domain-Policies` header tells some clients (mostly Adobe products) your domain's policy for loading cross-domain content.
[src:helmet-security/helmetjs-helmet] Helmet disables browsers' buggy cross-site scripting filter by setting the legacy `X-XSS-Protection` header to `0`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The primary use case for CSP is to control which resources, in particular JavaScript resources, a document is allowed to load.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This is mainly used as a defense against cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, in which an attacker is able to inject malicious code into the victim's site.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A CSP can have other purposes as well, including defending against clickjacking and helping to ensure that a site's pages will be loaded over HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In this guide we'll start by describing how a CSP is delivered to a browser and what it looks like at a high level.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Restrict embedding, to protect against clickjacking.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Upgrade insecure requests, to help ensure that all resources are served over HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Require the use of trusted types, to help defend against client-side XSS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Note that there's no dependency between the different use cases: if you want to add clickjacking protection but not XSS mitigation, you can just add the directives for that use case.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Finally we'll describe strategies for deploying a CSP and tools that can help to make this process easier.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A CSP should be delivered to the browser in the `Content-Security-Policy` response header.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] It should be set on all responses to all requests, not just the main document.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] You can also specify it using the `http-equiv` attribute of your document's `<meta>` element, and this is a useful option for some use cases, such as a client-side-rendered single page app which has only static resources, because you can then avoid relying on any server infrastructure.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] However, this option does not support all CSP features.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The policy is specified as a series of *directives*, separated by semi-colons.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Each directive controls a different aspect of the security policy.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Each directive has a name, followed by a space, followed by a value.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Different directives can have different syntaxes.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The first directive, `default-src`, tells the browser to load only resources that are same-origin with the document, unless other more specific directives set a different policy for other resource types.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The second, `img-src`, tells the browser to load images that are same-origin or that are served from `example.com`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In the next section, we'll look at the tools available to control resource loads, which is the main function of a CSP.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A CSP can be used to control the resources that a document is allowed to load.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This is primarily used for protection against cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In this section we'll first see how controlling resource loads can help protect against XSS, then at the tools CSP provides to control what resources are loaded.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Finally we'll describe one particular recommended strategy, which is called a "Strict CSP".
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A cross-site scripting (XSS) attack is one in which an attacker is able to execute their code in the context of the target website.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] An XSS attack is possible when a website accepts some input which might have been crafted by an attacker (for example, URL parameters, or a comment on a blog post) and then includes it in the page without *sanitizing* it: that is, without ensuring that it can't be executed as JavaScript.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Websites should protect themselves against XSS by sanitizing this input before including it in the page.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] By controlling resource loading, a CSP can provide protection against all of these.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In the next section we'll go over the tools CSP provides to do these things.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Fetch directives are used to specify a particular category of resource that a document is allowed to load — such as JavaScript, CSS stylesheets, images, fonts, and so on.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] There are different fetch directives for different types of resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] One special fetch directive is `default-src`, which sets a fallback policy for all resources whose directives are not explicitly listed.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] For the complete set of fetch directives, see the reference documentation.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Each fetch directive is specified as either the single keyword `'none'` or one or more *source expressions*, separated by spaces.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] When more than one source expression is listed: if any of the methods allow the resource, then the resource is allowed.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In the next few sections we'll describe some of the ways you can use source expressions to control resource loads.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Note that although we're describing them separately, these expressions can in general be combined: for example, a single fetch directive may include nonces as well as hostnames.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] To block a resource type entirely, use the `'none'` keyword.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Note that `'none'` cannot be combined with any other method in a particular directive: in practice, if any other source expressions are given alongside `'none'`, then they are ignored.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A `nonce` is the recommended approach for restricting the loading of `<script>` and `<style>` resources.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The server then includes this value as the value of the `nonce` attribute of all the `<script>` and/or `<style>` tags that they intend to include in the document.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The browser compares the two values, and loads the resource only if they match.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The idea is that even if an attacker can insert some JavaScript into the page, they won't know which nonce the server is going to use, so the browser will refuse to run the script.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] For this approach to work, it must not be possible for an attacker to guess the nonce.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This in turn means that the server cannot serve static HTML, because it must insert a new nonce each time.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Typically the server would use a templating engine to insert the nonce.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] On every request, the server generates a new nonce, inserts it into the CSP and into the `<script>` tags in the returned document.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] It's important that the server uses some kind of templating to insert nonces, and does not just insert them into all `<script>` tags: otherwise, the server might inadvertently insert nonces into scripts that were injected by an attacker.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Note that nonces can only be used for elements that have a `nonce` attribute: that is, only `<script>` and `<style>` elements.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Fetch directives can also use a hash of the script to guarantee its integrity.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] 3. appends a prefix identifying the hash algorithm used (one of `sha256-`, `sha384-`, or `sha512-`).
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] When the browser receives the document, it hashes the script, compares the result with the value from the header, and loads the script only if they match.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] External scripts must also include the `integrity` attribute for this method to work.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Fetch directives can list a scheme, like `https:`, to allow resources that are served using that scheme.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Fetch directives can control resource loads based on where the resource is located.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] You can also specify one or more hostnames, potentially including wildcards, and only resources served from those hosts will be allowed.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This might be used, for example, to allow content to be served from a trusted CDN.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] If a CSP contains either a `default-src` or a `script-src` directive, then inline JavaScript will not be allowed to execute unless extra measures are taken to enable it.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `unsafe-inline` keyword can be used to override this restriction.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Inline `<script>` elements are allowed if they are protected by a nonce or a hash, as described above.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] If a directive contains nonce or hash expressions, then the `unsafe-inline` keyword is ignored by browsers.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Like inline JavaScript, if a CSP contains either a `default-src` or a `script-src` directive, then `eval()` and similar APIs will not be allowed to execute.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `unsafe-eval` keyword can be used to override this behavior, and as with `unsafe-inline`, and for the same reasons: **developers should avoid `unsafe-eval`**.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Sometimes it can be difficult to remove usages of `eval()` and the other methods: in these situations, the Trusted Types API can make it safer, by ensuring that the input meets a defined policy.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `trusted-types-eval` keyword should be used to override the behavior in this case.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Unlike `unsafe-inline` it only overrides the behavior in browser when trusted types are supported and enabled; which ensures that the methods will remain blocked on browsers that don't support trusted types.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Unlike `unsafe-inline`, the `unsafe-eval` keyword does still work in a directive that contains nonce or hash expressions.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] To control script loading as a mitigation against XSS, recommended practice is to use nonce- or hash- based fetch directives.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Nonce-based directives are easier to maintain if you can generate responses, including the content itself, dynamically.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Otherwise, you need to use hash-based directives.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The problem with hash-based directives is that you need to recalculate and reapply the hash if any change is made to the script contents.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] As presented above, the strict CSP is difficult to implement when you use scripts which are not under your control.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] If a third-party script loads any additional scripts, or uses any inline scripts, then this will fail, because the third-party script won't pass the nonce or hash through.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `strict-dynamic` keyword is provided to help with this problem.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] It is a keyword that can be included in a fetch directive, and it has the effect that if a script has a nonce or a hash attached to it, then that script will be allowed to load further scripts which do not themselves have nonces or hashes.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] That is, the trust placed in a script by a nonce or hash is passed on to scripts that the original script loads (and scripts that *they* load, and so on).
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The "main.js" script will be allowed to load, because its hash matches the value in the CSP.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] But its attempt to load "main2.js" will fail.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `'strict-dynamic'` keyword makes it much easier to create and maintain nonce- or hash-based CSPs, especially when a website uses third-party scripts.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] It does make your CSP less secure, though, because if the scripts you include create `<script>` elements based on potential sources of XSS, then the CSP will not protect them.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] We've seen above that inline JavaScript is disallowed by default in a CSP.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] With nonces or hashes, a developer can use inline `<script>` tags, but you'll still need to refactor code to remove other disallowed patterns, including inline event handlers, `javascript:` URLs, and uses of `eval()`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `frame-ancestors` directive can be used to control which documents, if any, are allowed to embed this document in a nested browsing context such as an `<iframe>`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This is an effective protection against clickjacking attacks, because these attacks depend on embedding the target site in a site controlled by the attacker.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The syntax of `frame-ancestors` is a subset of the fetch directive syntax: you can provide the single keyword value `'none'` or one or more source expressions.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] However, the only source expressions you can use are schemes, hostnames, or the `'self'` keyword value.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This directive is a more flexible replacement for the `X-Frame-Options` header.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Web developers are strongly encouraged to serve all their content over HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This is called *mixed content*, and the presence of insecure resources greatly weakens the protection afforded by HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Under the mixed content algorithm that browsers implement, if a document is served over HTTPS, insecure resources are categorized into "upgradable content" and "blockable content".
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Upgradable content is upgraded to HTTPS, and blockable content is blocked, potentially breaking the page.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The ultimate solution to mixed content is for developers to load all resources over HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] However, even if a site is actually able to serve all content over HTTPS, it can still be very difficult (or even effectively impossible, where archived content is concerned) for a developer to rewrite all the URLs the site uses to load resources.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `upgrade-insecure-requests` directive is intended to solve this problem.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] However, top-level navigation requests whose target is a different origin will not be upgraded.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The browser will automatically upgrade both of these requests to HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The browser will upgrade the first link to HTTPS, but not the second, as it is navigating to a different origin.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This directive is not a substitute for the `Strict-Transport-Security` header (also known as HSTS), because it does not upgrade external links to a site.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Sites should include this directive and the `Strict-Transport-Security` header.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The `require-trusted-types-for` and `trusted-types` directives can be used to enforce the Trusted Types API.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This allows you to defend against client-side cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks by mandating that any input must be passed through a transformation function, providing an opportunity to make it safe before it is sent to a web platform API that might otherwise execute it as code.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Some APIs in the web platform are known as *injection sinks*.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] These are APIs that can be passed some input, usually in the form of a string, and that can interpret that input as code.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] In this guide we've already seen `eval()`, but there are many other injection sinks, such as `Element.innerHTML` or `Document.write()`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] If an attacker can supply some specially crafted input to your website, and your website passes it to one of these injection sinks, then the attacker can execute malicious code.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Some injection sinks, like `eval()`, are very hard to use safely, and we've seen that a CSP will typically block them entirely.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Others can be made safer if the input to them is processed so as to remove unsafe elements.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] With the Trusted Types API, you can pass *trusted types* into injection sinks, instead of strings.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Trusted types are objects that result from passing potentially dangerous input through a transformation function.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This transformation typically sanitizes the input, by removing any elements that might make it executable (such as `<script>` tags).
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] By default, your code could choose to pass trusted types or unsanitized strings to injection sinks.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] However, if you include the `require-trusted-types-for` directive in your CSP, and give it a value of `'script'`, then the browser will only allow your site to pass trusted types to injection sinks.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Trusted type objects are created using a user-defined *policy* object.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Your code can create any kind of policy object, including ones whose transformation function doesn't actually sanitize the input, and therefore doesn't protect you.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] To minimize this risk, you can include the `trusted-types` directive.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This lists the names of acceptable policies, and the browser will only allow those named policies to be used.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] To ease deployment, CSP can be deployed in report-only mode.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The policy is not enforced, but any violations are sent to the reporting endpoint specified in the policy.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Additionally, a report-only header can be used to test a future revision to a policy without actually deploying it.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] If both a `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only` header and a `Content-Security-Policy` header are present in the same response, both policies are honored.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The policy specified in `Content-Security-Policy` headers is enforced while the `Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only` policy generates reports but is not enforced.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] Note that unlike a normal content security policy, a report-only policy cannot be delivered in a `<meta>` element.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The recommended method for reporting CSP violations is to use the Reporting API, declaring endpoints in `Reporting-Endpoints` and specifying one of them as the CSP reporting target using the `Content-Security-Policy` header's `report-to` directive.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] A server can inform clients where to send reports using the `Reporting-Endpoints` HTTP response header.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] This header defines one or more endpoint URLs as a comma-separated list.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] You can then use the `Content-Security-Policy` header's `report-to` directive to specify that a particular defined endpoint should be used for reporting.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] When a CSP violation occurs, the browser sends the report as a JSON object to the specified endpoint via an HTTP `POST` operation, with a `Content-Type` of `application/reports+json`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The report is a serialized form of the `CSPViolationReport` object containing a `type` property with a value of `"csp-violation"`.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] You need to set up a server to receive reports with the given JSON format and content type.
[src:helmet-security/http-csp] The server handling these requests can then store or process the incoming reports in a way that best suits your needs.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] include the representation data in the body.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The following is a request with no body.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:helmet-security/http-header] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The IANA registry lists headers, including information about their status.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contain more information about the resource to be fetched, or about the client requesting the resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Hold additional information about the response, like its location or about the server providing it.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contain information about the body of the resource, like its MIME type, or encoding/compression applied.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contain representation-independent information about payload data, including content length and the encoding used for transport.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] These headers *must* be transmitted to the final recipient of the message: the server for a request, or the client for a response.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Intermediate proxies must retransmit these headers unmodified and caches must store them.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] These headers are meaningful only for a single transport-level connection, and *must not* be retransmitted by proxies or cached.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Note that only hop-by-hop headers may be set using the `Connection` header.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Defines the authentication method that should be used to access a resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contains the credentials to authenticate a user-agent with a server.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Defines the authentication method that should be used to access a resource behind a proxy server.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contains the credentials to authenticate a user agent with a proxy server.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The time, in seconds, that the object has been in a proxy cache.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Directives for caching mechanisms in both requests and responses.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Clears browsing data (e.g., cookies, storage, cache) associated with the requesting website.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The date/time after which the response is considered stale.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Specifies a set of rules that define how a URL's query parameters will affect cache matching.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] These rules dictate whether the same URL with different URL parameters should be saved as separate browser cache entries.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The last modification date of the resource, used to compare several versions of the same resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is less accurate than `ETag`, but easier to calculate in some environments.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Conditional requests using `If-Modified-Since` and `If-Unmodified-Since` use this value to change the behavior of the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A unique string identifying the version of the resource.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Conditional requests using `If-Match` and `If-None-Match` use this value to change the behavior of the request.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Makes the request conditional, and applies the method only if the stored resource matches one of the given ETags.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Makes the request conditional, and applies the method only if the stored resource *doesn't* match any of the given ETags.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] This is used to update caches (for safe requests), or to prevent uploading a new resource when one already exists.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Makes the request conditional, and expects the resource to be transmitted only if it has been modified after the given date.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] This is used to transmit data only when the cache is out of date.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Makes the request conditional, and expects the resource to be transmitted only if it has not been modified after the given date.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] This ensures the coherence of a new fragment of a specific range with previous ones, or to implement an optimistic concurrency control system when modifying existing documents.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Determines how to match request headers to decide whether a cached response can be used rather than requesting a fresh one from the origin server.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Controls whether the network connection stays open after the current transaction finishes.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Controls how long a persistent connection should stay open.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] For more details, refer to the Content negotiation article.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Informs the server about the types of data that can be sent back.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The encoding algorithm, usually a compression algorithm, that can be used on the resource sent back.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Informs the server about the human language the server is expected to send back.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] This is a hint and is not necessarily under the full control of the user: the server should always pay attention not to override an explicit user choice (like selecting a language from a dropdown).
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A *request content negotiation* response header that advertises which media type the server is able to understand in a `PATCH` request.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A *request content negotiation* response header that advertises which media type the server is able to understand in a `POST` request.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates expectations that need to be fulfilled by the server to properly handle the request.
