[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates whether a browser should be allowed to render a page in a `<frame>`, `<iframe>`, `<embed>` or `<object>`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A cross-domain policy file may grant clients, such as Adobe Acrobat or Apache Flex (among others), permission to handle data across domains that would otherwise be restricted due to the Same-Origin Policy.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The `X-Permitted-Cross-Domain-Policies` header overrides such policy files so that clients still block unwanted requests.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] May be set by hosting environments or other frameworks and contains information about them while not providing any usefulness to the application or its visitors.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Unset this header to avoid exposing potential vulnerabilities.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Fetch metadata request headers provide information about the context from which the request originated.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A server can use them to make decisions about whether a request should be allowed, based on where the request came from and how the resource will be used.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates the relationship between a request initiator's origin and its target's origin.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is a Structured Header whose value is a token with possible values `cross-site`, `same-origin`, `same-site`, and `none`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates the request's mode to a server.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is a Structured Header whose value is a token with possible values `cors`, `navigate`, `no-cors`, `same-origin`, and `websocket`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates whether or not a navigation request was triggered by user activation.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is a Structured Header whose value is a boolean so possible values are `?0` for false and `?1` for true.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is a Structured Header whose value is a token with possible values `audio`, `audioworklet`, `document`, `embed`, `empty`, `font`, `image`, `manifest`, `object`, `paintworklet`, `report`, `script`, `serviceworker`, `sharedworker`, `style`, `track`, `video`, `worker`, and `xslt`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The following request headers are not *strictly* "fetch metadata request headers", but similarly provide information about the context of how a resource will be used.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates the purpose of the request, when the purpose is something other than immediate use by the user-agent.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The header currently has one possible value, `prefetch`, which indicates that the resource is being fetched preemptively for a possible future navigation.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] A request header sent in preemptive request to `fetch()` a resource during service worker boot.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The value, which is set with `NavigationPreloadManager.setHeaderValue()`, can be used to inform a server that a different resource should be returned than in a normal `fetch()` operation.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] These headers enable an enhanced workflow for the Storage Access API.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates the "storage access status" for the current fetch context, which will be one of `none`, `inactive`, or `active`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] The server may respond with `Activate-Storage-Access` to request that the browser activate an `inactive` permission and retry the request, or to load a resource with access to its third-party cookies if the status is `active`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Used in response to `Sec-Fetch-Storage-Access` to indicate that the browser can activate an existing permission for secure access and retry the request with cookies, or load a resource with cookie access if it already has an activated permission.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Response header used to specify server endpoints where the browser should send warning and error reports when using the Reporting API.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Specifies the form of encoding used to safely transfer the resource to the user.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Specifies the transfer encodings the user agent is willing to accept.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Allows the sender to include additional fields at the end of chunked message.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Response header that indicates that the server is willing to upgrade to a WebSocket connection.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In requests, this header indicates the WebSocket extensions supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In responses, it indicates the extension selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Request header containing a key that verifies that the client explicitly intends to open a `WebSocket`.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In requests, this header indicates the sub-protocols supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In responses, it indicates the sub-protocol selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In requests, this header indicates the version of the WebSocket protocol used by the client.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] In responses, it is sent only if the requested protocol version is not supported by the server, and lists the versions that the server supports.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Used to list alternate ways to reach this service.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Used to identify the alternative service in use.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Contains the date and time at which the message was originated.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] This entity-header field provides a means for serializing one or more links in HTTP headers.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] It is semantically equivalent to the HTML `<link>` element.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Indicates how long the user agent should wait before making a follow-up request.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Communicates one or more metrics and descriptions for the given request-response cycle.
[src:helmet-security/http-headers] Included in fetches for a service worker's script resource.
